To determine the number of ways Anna can build the tower, we can use the concept of combinations. We have 5 discs, and we need to choose 3 of them to form the tower. The order in which we choose the discs doesn't matter, so we can use combinations.

The number of ways to choose 3 discs out of 5 is given by the combination formula:

C(n, k) = n! / (k!(n-k)!)

where n is the total number of items (in this case, 5 discs), k is the number of items to choose (in this case, 3 discs), and! denotes the factorial function.

C(5, 3) = 5! / (3!(5-3)!)
= 5! / (3!2!)
= (5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1) / ((3 × 2 × 1)(2 × 1))
= (5 × 4) / (2 × 1)
= 10

So, there are 10 ways for Anna to build the tower using the given discs. The answer is \boxed{10}.
